# Copy constructors
    Let’s imagine you’re building a library management system, and you’ve created a class called Book.
    This class stores details about a book, such as its title and number of pages.

    Now, suppose you already have one book object. Later on, you want to create another book object with the exact
    same details — maybe it’s a second copy of the same book, or you want to test something without changing the original.

    At this point, a common question arises:

    "How can I create a new object that has the same values as an existing one, without manually setting each value again?"
    One way to do this is to manually copy the values, like this:
        Book b1 = new Book("Java Fundamentals", 300);
        Book b2 = new Book();
        b2.title = b1.title;
        b2.pages = b1.pages;

    Yes, this works — but only when your class has just a few variables.

    Now if your Book class has 10 or more fields — like author, publisher, edition, price, ISBN, etc. Manually copying each one
    becomes tiring, easy to mess up, and hard to maintain. What if you forget to copy one of the fields? Or what if the class changes in the future?

    This is exactly where the copy constructor becomes useful. It offers a cleaner, more reliable way to create a new object with the
    same values as an existing one — in just one line of code.

Q1. What Exactly Is a Copy Constructor? 💡
Standard Definition:
    A copy constructor in Java is a special constructor that takes another object of the same class as its parameter and copies its values into the new object.

Q2. Why Is It Important? 🎯
    The copy constructor is important for several reasons:
        1. It allows you to create a new object with the same data as an existing object
        2. It avoids repeating the same assignments manually for every field
        3. It keeps your code clean, short, and easy to understand
        4. It makes sure the new object is separate — so changes to it don’t affect the original
        5. It gives your class a professional design, especially in real-world applications

    In short, copy constructors give you control, simplicity, and safety when working with objects that need to be duplicated.

# Syntax for Copy Constructor 🔍:
    Here are some basic things to know about copy constructors:
        1. A copy constructor has this general form:
                ClassName(ClassName object) {
                    this.field1 = object.field1;
                    this.field2 = object.field2;
                    // ...and so on
                }
        2. The constructor takes one argument, which is an object of the same class
        3. It copies each variable from the existing object to the new object
        4. Java does not provide a copy constructor by default — you must write it yourself
        5. It creates a deep copy for simple types (like int, String), but for objects, you may need to write a custom deep copy if needed
        6. The new object and the original are stored in different memory locations — so they don’t affect each other

# Common Interview Questions:

    Q1: What is a copy constructor?
        A constructor that takes an object of the same class and copies its data into a new object.

    Q2: Does Java automatically create a copy constructor?
        No. You need to write your own copy constructor if you want to use it.

    Q3: Why not just assign values manually instead of using a copy constructor?
        Manual copying takes more time, more code, and is easy to mess up. A copy constructor is clean, short, and consistent.

    Q4: What kind of copy does a copy constructor perform?
        By default, it performs a shallow copy. For complex objects, you’ll need to write logic for a deep copy.

    Q5: Can I overload a copy constructor?
        Yes. Like any constructor, you can overload it — but the common pattern is to have one copy constructor taking a single object.